1. Pipeline Architecture:
    - A pipeline is the automated workflow that defines the steps code goes through—from commit to production. Pipeline architecture involves how you design, organize, and manage these workflows.

2. Monorepo vs Multi-repo Pipelines:
    - Monorepo: All projects/services live in one repository.
        - Pros: Easier to manage shared dependencies and libraries.
                One CI/CD pipeline can orchestrate builds for multiple services.
        - Cons: Pipelines can get complex as number of services grows.
                Build times may be longer if not optimized.
        - Example: Google, Facebook use monorepos internally.
    - Multi-repo: Each project/service has its own repository.
        - Pros: Pipelines are simpler per service.
                Teams can work independently.
        - Cons: Harder to manage cross-service dependencies.
                Requires orchestrating multiple pipelines if a change impacts many services.
        - Example: Many small startups prefer multi-repo for microservices.
    - Handling multiple projects/services efficiently:
        - Trigger pipelines selectively:
            Only build/test/deploy the services that actually changed.
            Use path filters or conditional jobs in your pipeline.
            Example: If service-A/ changed, run tests and deploy only for Service A, not the entire repo.

3. Pipeline as Code:
    - Modern CI/CD uses Pipeline as Code, meaning the pipeline itself is defined and versioned in code—just like your application code.
    - Benefits:
        Reusable, modular, and maintainable.
        Version-controlled, so changes to the pipeline are auditable.
        Easy to share templates across teams.
    - Examples:
        - Jenkinsfile (for Jenkins):
        pipeline {
            agent any
            stages {
                stage('Install Dependencies') {
                    steps {
                        echo 'Installing Node.js dependencies...'
                        sh 'npm install'
                    }
                }

                stage('Run Tests') {
                    steps {
                        echo 'Running tests...'
                        sh 'npm test'
                    }
                }

                stage('Build') {
                    steps {
                        echo 'Building the app...'
                        sh 'npm run build'
                    }
                }

                stage('Deploy') {
                    steps {
                        echo 'Deploying the app...'
                        sh './deploy.sh'
                    }
                }
            }
            post {
                always {
                    echo 'Pipeline finished.'
                }
                success {
                    echo 'Pipeline succeeded!'
                }
                failure {
                    echo 'Pipeline failed!'
                }
            }
        }
        - GitHub Actions YAML:
        name: CI Pipeline
        on:
            push:
                paths:
                    - 'service-A/**'
                    - 'shared-lib/**'
        jobs:
            build:
                runs-on: ubuntu-latest
            steps:
                - name: Checkout repository
                    uses: actions/checkout@v3
                - name: Setup Node.js
                    uses: actions/setup-node@v3
                    with:
                        node-version: '18' # Change to your Node version
                - name: Install Dependencies
                    run: npm install
                - name: Run Tests
                    run: npm test
                - name: Build Application
                    run: npm run build
                - name: Deploy
                    run: ./deploy.sh

4. Conditional Steps:
    - Conditional steps allow pipelines to run only when necessary.
    - Purpose: Save resources, speed up CI/CD, avoid deploying unchanged services.
    - Techniques:
        Path filters (trigger jobs only if certain directories/files change)
            GitHub Actions example:
                on:
                    push:
                        paths:
                            - 'service-A/**'
                            - 'service-B/**'
        Environment checks (deploy to staging only, production later)
        Manual approvals (require human intervention for critical environments)
        Dynamic pipelines (Jenkins, GitLab CI can decide at runtime which stages to run)